    [DCS 00:22:42.067] Pipeline > Entry 3:
    
    [DCS 00:22:42.067] Pipeline >   Request: How do I cherry-pick a specific commit onto my branch?
    
    [DCS 00:22:42.067] Pipeline >   Response: Use `git cherry-pick <commit-hash>` to apply a specific commit from another branch onto your current branch. This creates a new commit with the same changes but a different hash. To cherry-pick a range of commits, use `git cherry-pick A..B` (exclusive of A) or `git cherry-pick A^..B` (inclusive). If conflicts arise, resolve them, then run `git cherry-pick --continue`. To abort, use `git cherry-pick --abort`. Add `-n` to apply changes without committing, letting you inspect or modify them first.
    [DCS 00:22:42.067] Pipeline > 
    
    [DCS 00:22:42.067] Pipeline > 
    
    [DCS 00:22:42.067] Pipeline > ---
    
    [DCS 00:22:42.067] Pipeline > ---- END TRANSIENT CONTEXT ----
    [DCS 00:22:42.067] Pipeline > Step 8: Sending second inference (user message + elected chunks)...
