    [DCS 00:22:45.610] Pipeline > ---- MODEL FINAL RESPONSE ----
    [DCS 00:22:45.610] Pipeline > To apply a specific commit from another branch, use:
    [DCS 00:22:45.610] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:22:45.610] Pipeline > ```bash
    [DCS 00:22:45.611] Pipeline > git cherry-pick <commit-hash>
    [DCS 00:22:45.611] Pipeline > ```
    [DCS 00:22:45.611] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:22:45.611] Pipeline > This command applies the changes from that specific commit onto your current branch, creating a new commit with the same changes but a different hash.
    [DCS 00:22:45.611] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:22:45.611] Pipeline > **Additional options:**
    [DCS 00:22:45.611] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:22:45.611] Pipeline > - **Cherry-pick a range of commits:**
    [DCS 00:22:45.611] Pipeline >   - `git cherry-pick A..B` (exclusive of commit A)
    [DCS 00:22:45.611] Pipeline >   - `git cherry-pick A^..B` (inclusive of commit A)
    [DCS 00:22:45.611] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:22:45.611] Pipeline > - **If conflicts occur:**
    [DCS 00:22:45.611] Pipeline >   - Resolve the conflicts manually
    [DCS 00:22:45.612] Pipeline >   - Run `git cherry-pick --continue` to finish
    [DCS 00:22:45.612] Pipeline >   - Or use `git cherry-pick --abort` to cancel the operation
    [DCS 00:22:45.612] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:22:45.612] Pipeline > - **Apply without committing:**
    [DCS 00:22:45.612] Pipeline >   - Add the `-n` flag: `git cherry-pick -n <commit-hash>`
    [DCS 00:22:45.612] Pipeline >   - This lets you inspect or modify the changes before committing
    [DCS 00:22:45.612] Pipeline > ---- END MODEL FINAL RESPONSE ----
