    [DCS 00:22:46.620] Pipeline > Entry 4:
    
    [DCS 00:22:46.620] Pipeline >   Request: How do I undo commits and reset my branch to a previous state?
    
    [DCS 00:22:46.620] Pipeline >   Response: Use `git reset` to move the branch pointer. `git reset --soft HEAD~1` undoes the last commit but keeps changes staged. `git reset --mixed HEAD~1` (the default) undoes the commit and unstages changes but keeps the files. `git reset --hard HEAD~1` discards the commit and all working directory changes — this is destructive. To recover from an accidental hard reset, use `git reflog` to find the lost commit hash and `git reset --hard <hash>` to restore it. Never force-reset commits that have been pushed to a shared branch.
    [DCS 00:22:46.620] Pipeline > 
    
    [DCS 00:22:46.620] Pipeline > 
    
