    [DCS 00:22:50.924] Pipeline > ---- MODEL FINAL RESPONSE ----
    [DCS 00:22:50.924] Pipeline > To undo your last commit in Git, use `git reset`:
    [DCS 00:22:50.924] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:22:50.924] Pipeline > - **`git reset --soft HEAD~1`** — Undoes the last commit but keeps your changes staged (ready to commit again)
    [DCS 00:22:50.924] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:22:50.924] Pipeline > - **`git reset --mixed HEAD~1`** (or just `git reset HEAD~1`) — Undoes the commit and unstages the changes, but keeps the files modified in your working directory
    [DCS 00:22:50.924] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:22:50.924] Pipeline > - **`git reset --hard HEAD~1`** — Completely discards the commit and all changes (destructive - use with caution!)
    [DCS 00:22:50.924] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:22:50.925] Pipeline > **Important safety notes:**
    [DCS 00:22:50.925] Pipeline > - If you accidentally use `--hard` and lose work, you can recover it using `git reflog` to find the lost commit hash, then `git reset --hard <hash>` to restore it
    [DCS 00:22:50.925] Pipeline > - Never force-reset commits that have already been pushed to a shared branch, as this will cause problems for other collaborators
    [DCS 00:22:50.925] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:22:50.925] Pipeline > Choose the option based on what you want to do with your changes after undoing the commit.
    [DCS 00:22:50.925] Pipeline > ---- END MODEL FINAL RESPONSE ----
