    [DCS 00:22:51.830] Pipeline > Entry 5:
    
    [DCS 00:22:51.830] Pipeline >   Request: How do I resolve a merge conflict in Git?
    
    [DCS 00:22:51.831] Pipeline >   Response: When a merge conflict occurs, Git marks the conflicting sections in the affected files with `<<<<<<<`, `=======`, and `>>>>>>>` markers. Open the file, decide which changes to keep (yours, theirs, or a combination), and remove the markers. After editing, stage the resolved file with `git add <filename>`. Once all conflicts are resolved, complete the merge with `git commit`. You can also use `git mergetool` to launch a visual merge tool. To abort the merge entirely, use `git merge --abort`.
    [DCS 00:22:51.831] Pipeline > 
    
    [DCS 00:22:51.831] Pipeline > 
    
    [DCS 00:22:51.831] Pipeline > ---
    
    [DCS 00:22:51.831] Pipeline > ---- END TRANSIENT CONTEXT ----
    [DCS 00:22:51.831] Pipeline > Step 8: Sending second inference (user message + elected chunks)...
    [DCS 00:22:56.799] Pipeline > Step 8: Model final response (1127 chars):
    [DCS 00:22:56.799] Pipeline > ---- MODEL FINAL RESPONSE ----
    [DCS 00:22:56.799] Pipeline > When a merge conflict occurs in Git, follow these steps to resolve it:
    [DCS 00:22:56.800] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:22:56.800] Pipeline > 1. **Identify the conflict**: Git marks conflicting sections in the affected files with special markers:
    [DCS 00:22:56.800] Pipeline >    - `<<<<<<<` marks the start of your changes
    [DCS 00:22:56.800] Pipeline >    - `=======` separates your changes from the incoming changes
    [DCS 00:22:56.800] Pipeline >    - `>>>>>>>` marks the end of the incoming changes
    [DCS 00:22:56.800] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:22:56.800] Pipeline > 2. **Edit the file**: Open the conflicting file and decide which changes to keep:
    [DCS 00:22:56.800] Pipeline >    - Keep your changes only
    [DCS 00:22:56.800] Pipeline >    - Keep the incoming changes only
    [DCS 00:22:56.800] Pipeline >    - Combine both sets of changes
    [DCS 00:22:56.800] Pipeline >    - Write something entirely new
    [DCS 00:22:56.801] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:22:56.801] Pipeline > 3. **Remove the conflict markers**: Delete the `<<<<<<<`, `=======`, and `>>>>>>>` lines after deciding what to keep.
    [DCS 00:22:56.801] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:22:56.801] Pipeline > 4. **Stage the resolved file**: Once you've edited the file, mark it as resolved:
    [DCS 00:22:56.801] Pipeline >    ```bash
    [DCS 00:22:56.801] Pipeline >    git add <filename>
    [DCS 00:22:56.801] Pipeline >    ```
    [DCS 00:22:56.801] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:22:56.801] Pipeline > 5. **Complete the merge**: After resolving all conflicts, finish the merge with:
    [DCS 00:22:56.801] Pipeline >    ```bash
    [DCS 00:22:56.801] Pipeline >    git commit
    [DCS 00:22:56.801] Pipeline >    ```
    [DCS 00:22:56.801] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:22:56.802] Pipeline > **Alternative options**:
    [DCS 00:22:56.802] Pipeline > - Use a visual merge tool: `git mergetool` launches a GUI tool to help resolve conflicts
    [DCS 00:22:56.802] Pipeline > - Abort the merge entirely: `git merge --abort` cancels the merge and returns to the pre-merge state
    [DCS 00:22:56.802] Pipeline > ---- END MODEL FINAL RESPONSE ----
