    [DCS 00:23:03.843] Pipeline > Entry 7:
    
    [DCS 00:23:03.843] Pipeline >   Request: How do list comprehensions work in Python?
    
    [DCS 00:23:03.843] Pipeline >   Response: A list comprehension provides a concise way to create lists. Syntax: `[expression for item in iterable if condition]`. Example: `[x**2 for x in range(10) if x % 2 == 0]` produces `[0, 4, 16, 36, 64]`. Nested comprehensions: `[x*y for x in range(3) for y in range(3)]`. For dictionaries, use `{k: v for k, v in pairs}`. For sets, use `{expr for item in iterable}`. Comprehensions are generally faster than equivalent `for` loops because they are optimized at the C level. Prefer generator expressions `(expr for ...)` when you only need to iterate once.
    [DCS 00:23:03.843] Pipeline > 
    
    [DCS 00:23:03.843] Pipeline > 
    
    [DCS 00:23:03.843] Pipeline > ---
    
    [DCS 00:23:03.844] Pipeline > ---- END TRANSIENT CONTEXT ----
    [DCS 00:23:03.844] Pipeline > Step 8: Sending second inference (user message + elected chunks)...
    [DCS 00:23:07.300] Pipeline > Step 8: Model final response (798 chars):
    [DCS 00:23:07.301] Pipeline > ---- MODEL FINAL RESPONSE ----
    [DCS 00:23:07.301] Pipeline > The Python syntax for list comprehension is:
    [DCS 00:23:07.301] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:23:07.301] Pipeline > ```python
    [DCS 00:23:07.301] Pipeline > [expression for item in iterable if condition]
    [DCS 00:23:07.301] Pipeline > ```
    [DCS 00:23:07.301] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:23:07.301] Pipeline > **Components:**
    [DCS 00:23:07.301] Pipeline > - **expression**: What you want to include in the new list
    [DCS 00:23:07.301] Pipeline > - **for item in iterable**: Loops through each item in the iterable
    [DCS 00:23:07.301] Pipeline > - **if condition**: Optional filter to include only items meeting the condition
    [DCS 00:23:07.301] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:23:07.301] Pipeline > **Example:**
    [DCS 00:23:07.302] Pipeline > ```python
    [DCS 00:23:07.302] Pipeline > [x**2 for x in range(10) if x % 2 == 0]
    [DCS 00:23:07.302] Pipeline > ```
    [DCS 00:23:07.302] Pipeline > This produces `[0, 4, 16, 36, 64]` by squaring only the even numbers from 0 to 9.
    [DCS 00:23:07.302] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:23:07.302] Pipeline > **Variations:**
    [DCS 00:23:07.302] Pipeline > - **Nested comprehensions**: `[x*y for x in range(3) for y in range(3)]`
    [DCS 00:23:07.302] Pipeline > - **Dictionary comprehensions**: `{k: v for k, v in pairs}`
    [DCS 00:23:07.302] Pipeline > - **Set comprehensions**: `{expr for item in iterable}`
    [DCS 00:23:07.302] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:23:07.302] Pipeline > List comprehensions are generally faster than equivalent `for` loops because they're optimized at the C level.
    [DCS 00:23:07.302] Pipeline > ---- END MODEL FINAL RESPONSE ----
