    [DCS 00:23:19.382] Pipeline > Entry 17:
    
    [DCS 00:23:19.382] Pipeline >   Request: How should I implement pagination in a REST API?
    
    [DCS 00:23:19.382] Pipeline >   Response: Two main approaches: offset-based and cursor-based. Offset-based: `GET /items?page=2&per_page=50` — simple but can skip or duplicate items if data changes between requests. Cursor-based: `GET /items?after=cursor_token&limit=50` — the cursor encodes the position (often an opaque encoded ID or timestamp), avoiding the shifting-offset problem. Return pagination metadata in a `Link` header (RFC 5988) or in the response body as `{ data: [...], next_cursor: "...", total: 1000 }`. For very large datasets, prefer cursor-based pagination. Always cap `per_page` at a maximum (e.g. 100) to prevent abuse.
    [DCS 00:23:19.382] Pipeline > 
    
    [DCS 00:23:19.382] Pipeline > 
    
    [DCS 00:23:19.383] Pipeline > ---
    
    [DCS 00:23:19.383] Pipeline > ---- END TRANSIENT CONTEXT ----
    [DCS 00:23:19.383] Pipeline > Step 8: Sending second inference (user message + elected chunks)...
    [DCS 00:23:24.649] Pipeline > Step 8: Model final response (1112 chars):
    [DCS 00:23:24.649] Pipeline > ---- MODEL FINAL RESPONSE ----
    [DCS 00:23:24.649] Pipeline > # Handling Pagination in REST APIs
    [DCS 00:23:24.650] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:23:24.650] Pipeline > There are **two main approaches** to pagination:
    [DCS 00:23:24.650] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:23:24.650] Pipeline > ## 1. Offset-Based Pagination
    [DCS 00:23:24.650] Pipeline > ```
    [DCS 00:23:24.650] Pipeline > GET /items?page=2&per_page=50
    [DCS 00:23:24.650] Pipeline > ```
    [DCS 00:23:24.650] Pipeline > - **Pros**: Simple and intuitive
    [DCS 00:23:24.650] Pipeline > - **Cons**: Can skip or duplicate items if data changes between requests (e.g., if items are added/deleted while paginating)
    [DCS 00:23:24.650] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:23:24.650] Pipeline > ## 2. Cursor-Based Pagination (Recommended for large datasets)
    [DCS 00:23:24.650] Pipeline > ```
    [DCS 00:23:24.651] Pipeline > GET /items?after=cursor_token&limit=50
    [DCS 00:23:24.651] Pipeline > ```
    [DCS 00:23:24.651] Pipeline > - The cursor encodes the position (often an opaque encoded ID or timestamp)
    [DCS 00:23:24.651] Pipeline > - **Pros**: Avoids the shifting-offset problem, stable results
    [DCS 00:23:24.651] Pipeline > - **Pros**: Better performance for very large datasets
    [DCS 00:23:24.651] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:23:24.651] Pipeline > ## Response Format
    [DCS 00:23:24.651] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:23:24.651] Pipeline > You can return pagination metadata in two ways:
    [DCS 00:23:24.651] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:23:24.651] Pipeline > ### Option A: Link Header (RFC 5988)
    [DCS 00:23:24.651] Pipeline > ```
    [DCS 00:23:24.652] Pipeline > Link: <https://api.example.com/items?after=xyz>; rel="next"
    [DCS 00:23:24.652] Pipeline > ```
    [DCS 00:23:24.652] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:23:24.652] Pipeline > ### Option B: Response Body
    [DCS 00:23:24.652] Pipeline > ```json
    [DCS 00:23:24.652] Pipeline > {
    [DCS 00:23:24.652] Pipeline >   "data": [...],
    [DCS 00:23:24.652] Pipeline >   "next_cursor": "...",
    [DCS 00:23:24.652] Pipeline >   "total": 1000
    [DCS 00:23:24.652] Pipeline > }
    [DCS 00:23:24.652] Pipeline > ```
    [DCS 00:23:24.652] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:23:24.653] Pipeline > ## Best Practices
    [DCS 00:23:24.653] Pipeline > - **Always cap `per_page`** at a maximum (e.g., 100) to prevent abuse
    [DCS 00:23:24.653] Pipeline > - **For very large datasets**, prefer cursor-based pagination
    [DCS 00:23:24.653] Pipeline > - Provide clear documentation about which pagination method you use
    [DCS 00:23:24.653] Pipeline > ---- END MODEL FINAL RESPONSE ----
