    [DCS 00:23:25.644] Pipeline > Entry 20:
    
    [DCS 00:23:25.644] Pipeline >   Request: How do Docker volumes work and when should I use bind mounts vs named volumes?
    
    [DCS 00:23:25.645] Pipeline >   Response: Docker has three storage types: named volumes, bind mounts, and tmpfs. Named volumes (`docker volume create mydata; docker run -v mydata:/app/data`) are managed by Docker, portable, and best for persistent data like databases. Bind mounts (`-v /host/path:/container/path`) map a host directory into the container — ideal for development so container code reflects local edits without rebuilding. tmpfs mounts store data in memory only, disappearing when the container stops — use for sensitive data you don't want persisted. For production databases, always use named volumes. For development source code hot-reloading, use bind mounts.
    [DCS 00:23:25.645] Pipeline > 
    
    [DCS 00:23:25.645] Pipeline > 
    
    [DCS 00:23:25.645] Pipeline > ---
    
    [DCS 00:23:25.645] Pipeline > ---- END TRANSIENT CONTEXT ----
