    [DCS 00:23:31.995] Pipeline > Based on the retrieved context, here are the key differences between named volumes and bind mounts in Docker:
    [DCS 00:23:31.995] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:23:31.996] Pipeline > ## **Named Volumes**
    [DCS 00:23:31.996] Pipeline > - **Managed by Docker**: Docker handles the storage location and lifecycle
    [DCS 00:23:31.996] Pipeline > - **Creation**: Created with `docker volume create mydata` and used with `-v mydata:/app/data`
    [DCS 00:23:31.996] Pipeline > - **Portability**: More portable across different systems
    [DCS 00:23:31.996] Pipeline > - **Best for**: Persistent data like databases in production environments
    [DCS 00:23:31.996] Pipeline > - **Storage location**: Docker manages where files are stored on the host
    [DCS 00:23:31.996] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:23:31.996] Pipeline > ## **Bind Mounts**
    [DCS 00:23:31.996] Pipeline > - **Direct host mapping**: Maps a specific host directory into the container
    [DCS 00:23:31.996] Pipeline > - **Usage**: `-v /host/path:/container/path`
    [DCS 00:23:31.996] Pipeline > - **Live updates**: Changes on the host immediately reflect in the container (and vice versa)
    [DCS 00:23:31.996] Pipeline > - **Best for**: Development workflows where you want code changes to be immediately available without rebuilding the container
    [DCS 00:23:31.997] Pipeline > - **Control**: You specify exactly where on the host filesystem the data lives
    [DCS 00:23:31.997] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:23:31.997] Pipeline > ## **When to Use Each**
    [DCS 00:23:31.997] Pipeline > - **Use named volumes** for production databases and any data that needs to persist reliably
    [DCS 00:23:31.997] Pipeline > - **Use bind mounts** for development when you want source code hot-reloading and need container changes to sync with your local files
    [DCS 00:23:31.997] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:23:31.997] Pipeline > In summary: named volumes are Docker-managed and production-friendly, while bind mounts give you direct host access and are ideal for development scenarios.
    [DCS 00:23:31.997] Pipeline > ---- END MODEL FINAL RESPONSE ----
