    [DCS 00:23:32.952] Pipeline > Entry 21:
    
    [DCS 00:23:32.952] Pipeline >   Request: How do multi-stage Docker builds work?
    
    [DCS 00:23:32.952] Pipeline >   Response: Multi-stage builds use multiple `FROM` instructions in a single Dockerfile. Each stage can have an alias: `FROM node:20 AS builder`. You can copy artifacts from one stage to another: `COPY --from=builder /app/dist /app/dist`. The final image contains only what the last `FROM` stage produces, discarding build tools and intermediate files. This dramatically reduces image size — a Node.js app's production image doesn't need npm or TypeScript. Use `--target builder` to stop at an intermediate stage for debugging. Order stages so the most cacheable layers come first to maximize Docker layer cache hits.
    [DCS 00:23:32.953] Pipeline > 
    
    [DCS 00:23:32.953] Pipeline > 
    
    [DCS 00:23:32.953] Pipeline > ---
    
    [DCS 00:23:32.953] Pipeline > ---- END TRANSIENT CONTEXT ----
    [DCS 00:23:32.953] Pipeline > Step 8: Sending second inference (user message + elected chunks)...
    [DCS 00:23:40.089] Pipeline > Step 8: Model final response (1445 chars):
    [DCS 00:23:40.089] Pipeline > ---- MODEL FINAL RESPONSE ----
    [DCS 00:23:40.089] Pipeline > To reduce Docker image size, use these key strategies:
    [DCS 00:23:40.089] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:23:40.089] Pipeline > **1. Multi-Stage Builds**
    [DCS 00:23:40.089] Pipeline > Use multiple `FROM` instructions in a single Dockerfile. Each stage can have an alias like `FROM node:20 AS builder`. Copy only necessary artifacts between stages: `COPY --from=builder /app/dist /app/dist`. The final image contains only what the last `FROM` stage produces, discarding build tools and intermediate files. This dramatically reduces size — a Node.js production image doesn't need npm or TypeScript.
    [DCS 00:23:40.089] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:23:40.089] Pipeline > **2. Choose Minimal Base Images**
    [DCS 00:23:40.089] Pipeline > - Use Alpine Linux variants (e.g., `node:20-alpine`) instead of full distributions
    [DCS 00:23:40.090] Pipeline > - Consider distroless images for production
    [DCS 00:23:40.090] Pipeline > - Use specific version tags, not `latest`
    [DCS 00:23:40.090] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:23:40.090] Pipeline > **3. Optimize Layer Caching**
    [DCS 00:23:40.090] Pipeline > - Order commands from least to most frequently changing
    [DCS 00:23:40.090] Pipeline > - Combine related `RUN` commands with `&&` to reduce layers
    [DCS 00:23:40.090] Pipeline > - Place dependency installation before copying application code
    [DCS 00:23:40.090] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:23:40.090] Pipeline > **4. Clean Up in the Same Layer**
    [DCS 00:23:40.090] Pipeline > ```dockerfile
    [DCS 00:23:40.090] Pipeline > RUN apt-get update && \
    [DCS 00:23:40.090] Pipeline >     apt-get install -y package && \
    [DCS 00:23:40.090] Pipeline >     apt-get clean && \
    [DCS 00:23:40.091] Pipeline >     rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*
    [DCS 00:23:40.091] Pipeline > ```
    [DCS 00:23:40.091] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:23:40.091] Pipeline > **5. Use .dockerignore**
    [DCS 00:23:40.091] Pipeline > Exclude unnecessary files (node_modules, .git, tests, documentation) from the build context.
    [DCS 00:23:40.091] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:23:40.091] Pipeline > **6. Remove Build Dependencies**
    [DCS 00:23:40.091] Pipeline > Install build tools, compile, then remove them in the same `RUN` command, or use multi-stage builds to leave them in earlier stages.
    [DCS 00:23:40.091] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:23:40.091] Pipeline > These techniques combined can reduce images from gigabytes to tens of megabytes.
    [DCS 00:23:40.091] Pipeline > ---- END MODEL FINAL RESPONSE ----
