    [DCS 00:23:41.020] Pipeline > Entry 22:
    
    [DCS 00:23:41.020] Pipeline >   Request: How does Docker networking work and how do containers communicate?
    
    [DCS 00:23:41.020] Pipeline >   Response: Docker provides several network drivers: bridge (default for standalone containers — containers on the same bridge network can communicate by container name), host (container shares the host network namespace — no network isolation), none (no network), and overlay (for multi-host Docker Swarm networks). In Docker Compose, services on the same Compose project share a default bridge network and can reach each other by service name as hostname. To expose a container port to the host, use `-p host_port:container_port`. Use `--network host` carefully — it bypasses Docker's network isolation. Inspect networks with `docker network inspect`.
    [DCS 00:23:41.021] Pipeline > 
    
    [DCS 00:23:41.021] Pipeline > 
    
    [DCS 00:23:41.021] Pipeline > ---
    
    [DCS 00:23:41.021] Pipeline > ---- END TRANSIENT CONTEXT ----
    [DCS 00:23:41.021] Pipeline > Step 8: Sending second inference (user message + elected chunks)...
    [DCS 00:23:47.254] Pipeline > Step 8: Model final response (1398 chars):
    [DCS 00:23:47.254] Pipeline > ---- MODEL FINAL RESPONSE ----
    [DCS 00:23:47.254] Pipeline > In Docker, containers communicate with each other through **Docker networks**. Here's how it works:
    [DCS 00:23:47.254] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:23:47.254] Pipeline > ## Network Drivers
    [DCS 00:23:47.254] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:23:47.255] Pipeline > Docker provides several network drivers:
    [DCS 00:23:47.255] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:23:47.255] Pipeline > 1. **Bridge (default)**: The default network for standalone containers. Containers on the same bridge network can communicate with each other using **container names** as hostnames.
    [DCS 00:23:47.255] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:23:47.255] Pipeline > 2. **Host**: The container shares the host's network namespace, meaning no network isolation. Use this carefully as it bypasses Docker's security isolation.
    [DCS 00:23:47.255] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:23:47.255] Pipeline > 3. **None**: No networking enabled for the container.
    [DCS 00:23:47.255] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:23:47.255] Pipeline > 4. **Overlay**: Used for multi-host communication in Docker Swarm environments.
    [DCS 00:23:47.256] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:23:47.256] Pipeline > ## Container-to-Container Communication
    [DCS 00:23:47.256] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:23:47.256] Pipeline > **Within the same network:**
    [DCS 00:23:47.256] Pipeline > - Containers can reach each other by **container name** (which acts as a hostname)
    [DCS 00:23:47.256] Pipeline > - Docker's internal DNS resolves container names to their IP addresses automatically
    [DCS 00:23:47.256] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:23:47.256] Pipeline > **In Docker Compose:**
    [DCS 00:23:47.256] Pipeline > - Services in the same Compose project automatically share a default bridge network
    [DCS 00:23:47.256] Pipeline > - Services can communicate using their **service name** as the hostname
    [DCS 00:23:47.256] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:23:47.256] Pipeline > ## Exposing Ports
    [DCS 00:23:47.256] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:23:47.257] Pipeline > To make a container port accessible from the host machine:
    [DCS 00:23:47.257] Pipeline > ```bash
    [DCS 00:23:47.257] Pipeline > docker run -p host_port:container_port image_name
    [DCS 00:23:47.257] Pipeline > ```
    [DCS 00:23:47.257] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:23:47.257] Pipeline > ## Inspecting Networks
    [DCS 00:23:47.257] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:23:47.257] Pipeline > You can view network details using:
    [DCS 00:23:47.257] Pipeline > ```bash
    [DCS 00:23:47.257] Pipeline > docker network inspect network_name
    [DCS 00:23:47.257] Pipeline > ```
    [DCS 00:23:47.257] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:23:47.258] Pipeline > This shows which containers are connected, their IP addresses, and network configuration.
    [DCS 00:23:47.258] Pipeline > ---- END MODEL FINAL RESPONSE ----
