    [DCS 00:23:48.164] Pipeline > --- Retrieved Context (transient — not stored in conversation history) ---
    
    [DCS 00:23:48.164] Pipeline > Entry 24:
    
    [DCS 00:23:48.164] Pipeline >   Request: What is the difference between unit tests and integration tests?
    
    [DCS 00:23:48.164] Pipeline >   Response: Unit tests test a single unit (function, method, class) in isolation, with all dependencies mocked or stubbed. They run fast, have no side effects, and pinpoint failures to a specific unit. Integration tests test how multiple components work together — for example, a service that reads from a real database or calls a real HTTP endpoint. They are slower, can have side effects (data written to a database), and require more setup. The testing pyramid suggests many unit tests, fewer integration tests, and even fewer end-to-end tests. Unit tests give you confident refactoring safety; integration tests give you confidence that the wired-up system works.
    [DCS 00:23:48.164] Pipeline > 
    
    [DCS 00:23:48.164] Pipeline > 
    
    [DCS 00:23:48.164] Pipeline > ---
    
    [DCS 00:23:48.164] Pipeline > ---- END TRANSIENT CONTEXT ----
    [DCS 00:23:48.164] Pipeline > Step 8: Sending second inference (user message + elected chunks)...
    [DCS 00:23:53.556] Pipeline > Step 8: Model final response (1032 chars):
    [DCS 00:23:53.556] Pipeline > ---- MODEL FINAL RESPONSE ----
    [DCS 00:23:53.556] Pipeline > Unit tests and integration tests differ in several key ways:
    [DCS 00:23:53.557] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:23:53.557] Pipeline > **Unit Tests:**
    [DCS 00:23:53.557] Pipeline > - Test a **single unit** (function, method, or class) in **isolation**
    [DCS 00:23:53.557] Pipeline > - All dependencies are **mocked or stubbed**
    [DCS 00:23:53.557] Pipeline > - **Run fast** with no side effects
    [DCS 00:23:53.557] Pipeline > - **Pinpoint failures** to a specific unit
    [DCS 00:23:53.557] Pipeline > - Provide confident refactoring safety
    [DCS 00:23:53.557] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:23:53.557] Pipeline > **Integration Tests:**
    [DCS 00:23:53.557] Pipeline > - Test how **multiple components work together**
    [DCS 00:23:53.557] Pipeline > - Use **real dependencies** (actual databases, HTTP endpoints, etc.)
    [DCS 00:23:53.557] Pipeline > - **Slower to execute** and can have side effects (like writing data to a database)
    [DCS 00:23:53.558] Pipeline > - Require more setup and infrastructure
    [DCS 00:23:53.558] Pipeline > - Provide confidence that the wired-up system works correctly
    [DCS 00:23:53.558] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:23:53.558] Pipeline > **Testing Strategy:**
    [DCS 00:23:53.558] Pipeline > The testing pyramid suggests you should have:
    [DCS 00:23:53.558] Pipeline > - **Many unit tests** (base of the pyramid)
    [DCS 00:23:53.558] Pipeline > - **Fewer integration tests** (middle)
    [DCS 00:23:53.558] Pipeline > - **Even fewer end-to-end tests** (top)
    [DCS 00:23:53.558] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:23:53.558] Pipeline > In summary: unit tests verify individual components work correctly in isolation, while integration tests verify that components work correctly when connected together in a more realistic environment.
    [DCS 00:23:53.558] Pipeline > ---- END MODEL FINAL RESPONSE ----
