    [DCS 00:23:55.235] Pipeline > Entry 26:
    
    [DCS 00:23:55.235] Pipeline >   Request: How do I write parameterized tests in xUnit?
    
    [DCS 00:23:55.235] Pipeline >   Response: xUnit supports parameterized tests through `[Theory]` combined with data sources. `[InlineData]` provides inline values: `[Theory][InlineData(1, 2, 3)][InlineData(10, 20, 30)] void Add_ReturnsSum(int a, int b, int expected)`. `[MemberData]` points to a static property or method returning `IEnumerable<object[]>`. `[ClassData]` uses a class implementing `IEnumerable<object[]>`. For data from external sources, create a custom `DataAttribute` by subclassing `DataAttribute`. Test runners display each theory case as a separate test result. Use `[Theory]` when the same logic should hold for multiple input/output combinations — it's far more readable than duplicated test methods.
    [DCS 00:23:55.235] Pipeline > 
    
    [DCS 00:23:55.235] Pipeline > 
    
    [DCS 00:23:55.236] Pipeline > ---
    
    [DCS 00:23:55.236] Pipeline > ---- END TRANSIENT CONTEXT ----
    [DCS 00:23:55.236] Pipeline > Step 8: Sending second inference (user message + elected chunks)...
    [DCS 00:24:02.159] Pipeline > Step 8: Model final response (1348 chars):
    [DCS 00:24:02.160] Pipeline > ---- MODEL FINAL RESPONSE ----
    [DCS 00:24:02.160] Pipeline > In xUnit, you write parameterized tests using the `[Theory]` attribute combined with data source attributes. Here's how:
    [DCS 00:24:02.160] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:24:02.160] Pipeline > ## Basic Approach with [InlineData]
    [DCS 00:24:02.160] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:24:02.160] Pipeline > The simplest method uses `[InlineData]` to provide inline values:
    [DCS 00:24:02.160] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:24:02.160] Pipeline > ```csharp
    [DCS 00:24:02.161] Pipeline > [Theory]
    [DCS 00:24:02.161] Pipeline > [InlineData(1, 2, 3)]
    [DCS 00:24:02.161] Pipeline > [InlineData(10, 20, 30)]
    [DCS 00:24:02.161] Pipeline > public void Add_ReturnsSum(int a, int b, int expected)
    [DCS 00:24:02.161] Pipeline > {
    [DCS 00:24:02.161] Pipeline >     // Test implementation
    [DCS 00:24:02.161] Pipeline > }
    [DCS 00:24:02.161] Pipeline > ```
    [DCS 00:24:02.162] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:24:02.162] Pipeline > ## Other Data Source Options
    [DCS 00:24:02.162] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:24:02.162] Pipeline > **[MemberData]** - Points to a static property or method that returns `IEnumerable<object[]>`:
    [DCS 00:24:02.162] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:24:02.162] Pipeline > ```csharp
    [DCS 00:24:02.162] Pipeline > [Theory]
    [DCS 00:24:02.162] Pipeline > [MemberData(nameof(TestData))]
    [DCS 00:24:02.163] Pipeline > public void MyTest(int value) { }
    [DCS 00:24:02.163] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:24:02.163] Pipeline > public static IEnumerable<object[]> TestData => new List<object[]>
    [DCS 00:24:02.163] Pipeline > {
    [DCS 00:24:02.163] Pipeline >     new object[] { 1 },
    [DCS 00:24:02.163] Pipeline >     new object[] { 2 }
    [DCS 00:24:02.163] Pipeline > };
    [DCS 00:24:02.163] Pipeline > ```
    [DCS 00:24:02.163] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:24:02.164] Pipeline > **[ClassData]** - Uses a class implementing `IEnumerable<object[]>`:
    [DCS 00:24:02.164] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:24:02.164] Pipeline > ```csharp
    [DCS 00:24:02.164] Pipeline > [Theory]
    [DCS 00:24:02.164] Pipeline > [ClassData(typeof(MyTestDataClass))]
    [DCS 00:24:02.164] Pipeline > public void MyTest(int value) { }
    [DCS 00:24:02.164] Pipeline > ```
    [DCS 00:24:02.164] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:24:02.164] Pipeline > **Custom DataAttribute** - For external data sources, create a custom attribute by subclassing `DataAttribute`.
    [DCS 00:24:02.165] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:24:02.165] Pipeline > ## Benefits
    [DCS 00:24:02.165] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:24:02.165] Pipeline > - Each theory case appears as a **separate test result** in test runners
    [DCS 00:24:02.165] Pipeline > - Much more **readable** than duplicating test methods
    [DCS 00:24:02.165] Pipeline > - Use `[Theory]` when the same logic should hold for multiple input/output combinations
    [DCS 00:24:02.165] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:24:02.165] Pipeline > This approach keeps your tests DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself) while providing clear test coverage across different scenarios.
    [DCS 00:24:02.165] Pipeline > ---- END MODEL FINAL RESPONSE ----
