    [DCS 00:24:17.100] Pipeline > None of the provided context entries relate to JWT (JSON Web Tokens) or API authentication mechanisms. The entries cover REST status codes, REST versioning, mocking in testing, pagination strategies, and git stash commands, but nothing about JWT.
    [DCS 00:24:17.100] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:24:17.100] Pipeline > Since the context doesn't contain relevant information, I'll answer directly:
    [DCS 00:24:17.100] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:24:17.100] Pipeline > **JWT (JSON Web Token)** is a compact, self-contained token format used for securely transmitting information between parties, commonly for API authentication.
    [DCS 00:24:17.100] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:24:17.101] Pipeline > ## How JWT Works:
    [DCS 00:24:17.101] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:24:17.101] Pipeline > **Structure:** A JWT has three parts separated by dots:
    [DCS 00:24:17.101] Pipeline > - **Header**: Algorithm and token type (e.g., `{"alg":"HS256","typ":"JWT"}`)
    [DCS 00:24:17.101] Pipeline > - **Payload**: Claims/data (user ID, roles, expiration, etc.)
    [DCS 00:24:17.101] Pipeline > - **Signature**: Cryptographic signature to verify integrity
    [DCS 00:24:17.101] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:24:17.101] Pipeline > **Authentication Flow:**
    [DCS 00:24:17.101] Pipeline > 1. **User logs in** with credentials
    [DCS 00:24:17.101] Pipeline > 2. **Server validates** and creates a JWT containing user info
    [DCS 00:24:17.101] Pipeline > 3. **Client receives** the token and stores it (localStorage, cookie)
    [DCS 00:24:17.101] Pipeline > 4. **Client sends token** in subsequent API requests (typically in `Authorization: Bearer <token>` header)
    [DCS 00:24:17.101] Pipeline > 5. **Server verifies** the signature and extracts user info from the payload
    [DCS 00:24:17.102] Pipeline > 6. **Server grants/denies** access based on token validity and claims
    [DCS 00:24:17.102] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:24:17.102] Pipeline > **Benefits:**
    [DCS 00:24:17.102] Pipeline > - Stateless (no server-side session storage needed)
    [DCS 00:24:17.102] Pipeline > - Scalable across multiple servers
    [DCS 00:24:17.102] Pipeline > - Contains user information (reducing database lookups)
    [DCS 00:24:17.102] Pipeline > 
    [DCS 00:24:17.102] Pipeline > **Security Notes:**
    [DCS 00:24:17.102] Pipeline > - Tokens should have expiration times
    [DCS 00:24:17.102] Pipeline > - Use HTTPS to prevent interception
    [DCS 00:24:17.102] Pipeline > - Store securely (avoid localStorage for sensitive apps)
    [DCS 00:24:17.102] Pipeline > - Implement refresh token patterns for long-lived sessions
    [DCS 00:24:17.103] Pipeline > ---- END MODEL FIRST RESPONSE ----
